In the guarantee contract, the parties agree that, if the debtor is unable to perform, the guarantor is liable for the guarantee as a general guarantee. 

 the guarantor of the general guarantee has the right to refuse to provide security to the creditor until the dispute in the main contract has been tried or settled and the debtor's property has been legally enforced for failure to perform, except in the following cases: 

(i) the debtor is unaccounted for and there is no property available for enforcement; 

(ii) the People's Court has accepted the debtor's insolvency case; 

(iii) the creditor has evidence that the debtor's property is insufficient to perform the entire debt or is incapable of performing the debt; 

(iv) the guarantor has indicated in writing that it has waived its right under this paragraph.

