Inheritants lose their inheritance rights in the following cases: 

(i) wilful killing of heirs; 

(ii) killing of other heirs in competition for inheritance; 

(iii) abandonment of heirs or abuse of heirs in aggravating circumstances; 

(iv) forgery, tampering, concealment or destruction of wills in aggravating circumstances; 

(v) aggravating circumstances in cases of fraud, coercion or obstruction of the creation, change or withdrawal of wills by heirs. 

) Inheritants have third to fifth acts in the preceding paragraph, in which there is a genuine act of repentance, or where the heir expresses forgiveness or subsequently lists them as heirs in the will, the heir shall not lose his inheritance rights. 

 Bequests have lost their right to bequests as defined in paragraph 1 of this article.

